{
  "text": "\u2423-Synuclein is a small abundant neuronal protein that is natively unstructured, but folds into amphipathic \u2423-helices in the presence of negatively charged lipids [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , binds to synaptobrevin-2/VAMP2 [CITATION_3] , and localizes to synaptic vesicles in nerve terminals [CITATION_4] . In vitro and in cultured cells and neurons, \u2423-synuclein promotes SNARE-complex assembly [CITATION_5] . Three synuclein genes are expressed in mammals that encode \u2423-synuclein, \u2424-synuclein, and \u2425-synuclein. \u2423/\u2424/\u2425-Synuclein triple knock-out (KO) mice develop progressive neuropathology and motor impairments, die prematurely, and exhibit impaired SNARE-complex assembly, which is consistent with the idea that \u2423-synuclein functions as a SNARE-complex chaperone [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "42665648",
